    mechanism:
      "**Vardenafil** (originally developed by Bayer / GSK and approved as Levitra in 2003; also marketed as Staxyn in orally-disintegrating tablet form) is a selective phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE5) inhibitor approved for erectile dysfunction (ED) treatment. The compound sits in the middle of the four major PDE5 inhibitors by both onset speed and duration — faster onset than Tadalafil but shorter duration; more potent per milligram than Sildenafil but with higher PDE5/PDE6 selectivity (reducing visual side effects). The catalog positions Vardenafil within the PDE5 form-selection framework established in the BATCH40 Tadalafil tile, where each PDE5 inhibitor's distinct pharmacokinetic and selectivity profile drives the appropriate use case. **Mechanism — PDE5 inhibition (shared with the PDE5 class)**: see the parent BATCH40 Tadalafil tile and BATCH39 Sildenafil tile for full PDE5 mechanism content. In summary, PDE5 inhibitors block the cyclic GMP-degrading enzyme phosphodiesterase type 5 in vascular smooth muscle. Sexual stimulation triggers nitric oxide release in the corpus cavernosum, activating guanylyl cyclase, increasing cGMP levels, and producing vasodilation that enables penile erection. PDE5 normally degrades cGMP, terminating the vasodilation signal. PDE5 inhibitors block this degradation, sustaining cGMP-mediated vasodilation and enabling sustained erection in response to sexual stimulation. The mechanism requires sexual stimulation (PDE5 inhibitors do not produce erection in the absence of NO release; this is why the class is permissive rather than directive). **Mechanism — Vardenafil's specific pharmacokinetic profile**: Vardenafil onset is 30-60 minutes post-dose (slightly faster than Sildenafil's 60 minutes, substantially faster than Tadalafil's 1-2 hours). Half-life is 4-6 hours (similar to Sildenafil; substantially shorter than Tadalafil's 17.5 hours). The pharmacokinetic profile positions Vardenafil for **on-demand use** (taken before anticipated sexual activity) rather than daily-use protocols. The shorter duration vs Tadalafil is a feature for some users (cleaner pharmacology, less drug accumulation) and a limitation for others (less spontaneity-friendly than Tadalafil's 36-hour window). **Mechanism — PDE6 selectivity (the visual side effect differentiator)**: PDE5 inhibitors have cross-reactivity with related phosphodiesterase isoforms. **PDE6** in retinal photoreceptors is the principal off-target concern — PDE6 inhibition produces visual disturbances (blue-tinged vision, photophobia, blurry vision). The PDE5/PDE6 selectivity ratio varies meaningfully across the four PDE5 inhibitors: **Sildenafil** has the lowest selectivity (~10:1) and the highest rate of visual side effects; **Vardenafil** has higher selectivity (~16:1) with reduced visual side effects; **Tadalafil** has different selectivity profile (more PDE11 cross-reactivity producing back / muscle pain in some users); **Avanafil** has the highest selectivity (~120:1) with the cleanest visual side effect profile. Vardenafil's middle-position selectivity makes it a reasonable choice for users with Sildenafil-induced visual side effects who want shorter-duration pharmacology than Tadalafil. **Mechanism — comparative potency**: Vardenafil is more potent per milligram than Sildenafil — the standard 10mg Vardenafil dose is approximately equivalent to 50mg Sildenafil in clinical effect. This is reflected in the dose ranges (Vardenafil 5-20mg vs Sildenafil 25-100mg) without functional difference at appropriate dose pairing. **Mechanism — DTC telemedicine 4-in-1 PDE5 chewables**: Vardenafil is one of the four PDE5 inhibitors offered in DTC telemedicine compounded chewable formulations alongside Sildenafil, Tadalafil, and Avanafil. The 4-in-1 compounded products provide low doses of all four PDE5 inhibitors in single chewable form, marketed for convenience and combined-mechanism positioning. The catalog's framing on these products is mechanism-honest: combined PDE5 inhibition at low individual doses is not pharmacologically additive in a useful way (PDE5 receptors are saturated by adequate dose of any single inhibitor; adding more PDE5 inhibitors does not produce additive vasodilation), so the 4-in-1 framing is more marketing convenience than pharmacological synergy. Users wanting effective PDE5 therapy are typically better served by adequate dose of a single PDE5 inhibitor matched to their use case rather than sub-therapeutic doses of all four. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability ~15% (variable); onset 30-60 minutes; peak plasma 1 hour; half-life 4-6 hours; CYP3A4 metabolism (substantial drug-drug interaction potential with CYP3A4 inhibitors and inducers); largely fecal elimination of metabolites. **Pharmaceutical status**: FDA-approved 2003 as Levitra; orally-disintegrating tablet form approved as Staxyn 2010; generic formulations widely available since 2018 patent expiration.",
