    mechanism:
      "**Avanafil** (originally developed by Tanabe Seiyaku, licensed to Vivus and now Metuchen Pharmaceuticals, FDA-approved as Stendra in 2012; also marketed as Spedra in European markets) is the newest-generation selective PDE5 inhibitor approved for erectile dysfunction (ED) treatment. The compound sits at the leading edge of the PDE5 inhibitor class with two principal differentiators: **the fastest onset of any PDE5 inhibitor** (clinical efficacy as early as 15 minutes post-dose) and **the highest PDE5/PDE6 selectivity** (~120:1 vs Sildenafil's ~10:1), producing the cleanest visual side effect profile in the class. The catalog positions Avanafil as the premium-tier PDE5 inhibitor — best pharmacokinetics and side effect profile, but with cost and availability premium over generic Sildenafil / Vardenafil / Tadalafil. This tile closes out the BATCH40 Tadalafil tile's PDE5 form-selection framework alongside the Vardenafil tile (preceding). **Mechanism — PDE5 inhibition (shared with the PDE5 class)**: see the parent BATCH40 Tadalafil tile, BATCH39 Sildenafil tile, and the preceding Vardenafil tile for full PDE5 mechanism content. In summary, PDE5 inhibitors block cyclic GMP-degrading enzyme phosphodiesterase type 5 in vascular smooth muscle. Sexual stimulation triggers nitric oxide release in the corpus cavernosum, activating guanylyl cyclase, increasing cGMP levels, and producing vasodilation enabling penile erection. PDE5 normally degrades cGMP; PDE5 inhibitors block this degradation, sustaining cGMP-mediated vasodilation. The mechanism requires sexual stimulation (PDE5 inhibitors are permissive rather than directive). **Mechanism — Avanafil's specific pharmacokinetic differentiation**: the principal Avanafil pharmacokinetic features that differentiate from older PDE5 inhibitors: **Rapid onset (15-30 minutes)** — clinical efficacy demonstrated as early as 15 minutes post-dose in Phase 3 trials; substantially faster than Vardenafil (30-60 min), Sildenafil (60 min), or Tadalafil (1-2 hours). The rapid onset is particularly relevant for spontaneity contexts and for users with anxiety about timing-driven sexual encounters. **Duration 5-10 hours** — moderate duration; longer than Vardenafil's 4-6 hours, shorter than Tadalafil's 17.5 hours; supports on-demand pharmacology without Tadalafil's extended-window pharmacology accumulation potential. **CYP3A4 metabolism** — like other PDE5 inhibitors; drug-drug interaction profile similar to Vardenafil. **Mechanism — PDE5 selectivity (the cleanest side effect profile)**: Avanafil's PDE5/PDE6 selectivity ratio (~120:1) is substantially higher than any other approved PDE5 inhibitor: Sildenafil ~10:1, Vardenafil ~16:1, Tadalafil different selectivity profile (more PDE11 cross-reactivity). The high PDE6 selectivity translates to: **minimal visual side effects** — blue-tinged vision, photophobia, blurry vision are rare with Avanafil vs common with Sildenafil; **no significant PDE11 cross-reactivity** — back pain and muscle aches that Tadalafil users sometimes experience are minimal with Avanafil; **cleaner overall side effect profile** — generally better-tolerated than older PDE5 inhibitors, particularly in users with prior PDE5 inhibitor intolerance. The selectivity differential is the principal pharmacological argument for Avanafil over older PDE5 inhibitors. **Mechanism — comparative potency**: standard Avanafil dose 100mg ≈ Sildenafil 50mg ≈ Vardenafil 10mg ≈ Tadalafil 10mg in clinical effect. Dose ranges are larger (50-200mg) reflecting the milligram-potency differential without functional difference at appropriate dose pairing. **Mechanism — DTC telemedicine 4-in-1 PDE5 chewables**: Avanafil is the fourth PDE5 inhibitor in the DTC compounded chewable products combining all four PDE5 inhibitors at low doses. See preceding Vardenafil tile for full framing of the 4-in-1 product category — the pharmacology is more marketing convenience than additive benefit; users wanting effective PDE5 therapy are typically better served by adequate dose of single PDE5 inhibitor matched to their use case. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability standard small-molecule; onset 15-30 minutes; peak plasma 30-45 minutes; half-life 5-10 hours; CYP3A4 metabolism (drug-drug interaction potential); largely fecal elimination of metabolites. **Pharmaceutical status**: FDA-approved 2012 as Stendra; substantially smaller market penetration than older PDE5 inhibitors despite better pharmacokinetic profile, principally due to brand-only pricing and generic competition from older agents.",
